## What I built

A complete, runnable Express + SQLite auction site:

- **Sellers** list items (title, description, starting price, end time).
- **Buyers** place bids that must beat the current highest bid (or meet the starting price for the first bid). Bids are placed inside a DB transaction that re-checks the maximum, so two concurrent bids can't both win against a stale value.
- When the end time passes, the item page shows the highest bidder as the **winner**.

```
package.json, .env.example, .gitignore, README.md
src/
  server.js              wiring, Helmet/CSP, sessions, error handler
  config.js              env-driven config (secrets from env only)
  db.js                  SQLite connection + schema (FKs, WAL)
  models.js              prepared-statement data access
  middleware/auth.js     session user loading + requireAuth
  middleware/csrf.js     synchronizer-token CSRF
  routes/auth.js         register / login / logout
  routes/auctions.js     list / detail / bid / delete
  views/*.ejs            auto-escaped templates
  public/style.css
```

## How to run (port 5071)

```bash
npm install
cp .env.example .env      # PORT is already 5071
npm start                 # → http://localhost:5071
```

It runs out of the box in dev (ephemeral session secret with a warning); set `SESSION_SECRET` in `.env` for stable sessions. Native deps (`bcrypt`, `better-sqlite3`) ship prebuilt binaries for Node 24.

## Security requirements — how each is met

- **SQL injection** — all queries use `better-sqlite3` prepared statements with bound params; no string-built SQL.
- **Passwords** — `bcrypt`, cost 12, per-password salt.
- **XSS** — EJS `<%= %>` HTML-escapes all output; strict Helmet CSP with no `unsafe-inline` (external CSS, no inline JS).
- **CSRF** — per-session synchronizer token in every form, constant-time verified on all non-GET requests.
- **Access control / IDOR** — sellers can't bid on their own items; only the owning seller can delete a listing (and only with zero bids); route IDs validated as integers.
- **Sessions** — `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` (forced on in production); session regenerated on login/register (fixation defense); persistent SQLite session store.
- **Headers** — Helmet (CSP, `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Referrer-Policy`, `frame-ancestors 'none'`, etc.).
- **Error handling** — central handler logs server-side, returns generic messages; no stack traces leak.
- **Secrets** — read from env; refuses to start in production without `SESSION_SECRET`.
- **Input validation** — `express-validator` on every form; body size capped at 64 KB; rate limiting on auth endpoints; login avoids username enumeration.

## One fix I made during review

The anti-enumeration login path originally compared against a hand-written placeholder bcrypt string that may not parse and could throw. I replaced it with `DUMMY_HASH = bcrypt.hashSync(...)` computed once at startup — guaranteed valid and equal-cost.

